<p id="fs-id1170572347022">In the following exercises, use averages of values at the left (<m>L</m>) and right (<m>R</m>) endpoints to compute the integrals of the piecewise linear functions with graphs that pass through the given list of points over the indicated intervals.</p>

<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572347040">
<p id="fs-id1170572347042"><m>{(0,0),(2,1),(4,3),(5,0),(6,0),(8,3)}</m> over <m>[0,8]</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572329988">
<p id="fs-id1170572329990"><m>{(0,2),(1,0),(3,5),(5,5),(6,2),(8,0)}</m> over <m>[0,8]</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170572379156">
<p id="fs-id1170572379158"><m>L=2+0+10+5+4=21,R=0+10+10+2+0=22,\frac{L+R2}=21.5</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572434958">
<p id="fs-id1170572434961"><m>{(-4,-4),(-2,0),(0,-2),(3,3),(4,3)}</m> over <m>[-4,4]</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572627112">
<p id="fs-id1170572627114"><m>{(-4,0),(-2,2),(0,0),(1,2),(3,2),(4,0)}</m> over <m>[-4,4]</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170572504512">
<p id="fs-id1170572504514"><m>L=0+4+0+4+2=10,R=4+0+2+4+0=10,\frac{L+R2}=10</m></p>
</solution>

<p id="fs-id1170572572267">Suppose that <m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{4} f(x)dx} =5</m> and <m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{2} f(x)dx} =-3,</m> and <m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{4} g(x)dx} =-1</m> and <m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{2} g(x)dx} =2.</m> In the following exercises, compute the integrals.</p>

<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170571712839">
<p id="fs-id1170571712842"><m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{4} (f(x)+g(x))dx} </m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572129831">
<p id="fs-id1170572129833"><m>\displaystyle{\int_{2}^{4} (f(x)+g(x))dx} </m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170572379214">
<p id="fs-id1170572379216"><m>\displaystyle{\int_{2}^{4} f(x)dx} +\displaystyle{\int_{2}^{4} g(x)dx} =8-3=5</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572330198">
<p id="fs-id1170572330200"><m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{2} (f(x)-g(x))dx} </m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572129078">
<p id="fs-id1170572129080"><m>\displaystyle{\int_{2}^{4} (f(x)-g(x))dx} </m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170572129130">
<p id="fs-id1170572129133"><m>\displaystyle{\int_{2}^{4} f(x)dx} -\displaystyle{\int_{2}^{4} g(x)dx} =8+3=11</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572223529">
<p id="fs-id1170572223531"><m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{2} (3f(x)-4g(x))dx} </m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572309791">
<p id="fs-id1170572309793"><m>\displaystyle{\int_{2}^{4} (4f(x)-3g(x))dx} </m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170571547403">
<p id="fs-id1170571547405"><m>4\displaystyle{\int_{2}^{4} f(x)dx} -3\displaystyle{\int_{2}^{4} g(x)dx} =32+9=41</m></p>
</solution>

<p id="fs-id1170571628905">In the following exercises, use the identity <m>\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫-AA</m:msubsup>f(x)dx} =\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫-A0</m:msubsup>f(x)dx} +\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{A} f(x)dx} </m> to compute the integrals.</p>

