</solution>

<p id="fs-id1170572309649">In the following exercises, approximate the average value using Riemann sums <m>L</m><sub>100</sub> and <m>R</m><sub>100</sub>. How does your answer compare with the exact given answer?</p>

<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572617925">
<p id="fs-id1170572617927"><emphasis effect="bold">[T]</emphasis> <m>y=\text{ ln }(x)</m> over the interval <m>[1,4];</m> the exact solution is <m>\frac{\text{ ln }(256)3}-1.</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572618040">
<p id="fs-id1170572554208"><emphasis effect="bold">[T]</emphasis> <m>y=<m:msup>ex\text{ / }2</m:msup></m> over the interval <m>[0,1];</m> the exact solution is <m>2(\sqrt{e}-1).</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170572554273">
<p id="fs-id1170572554275"><m><m:msub>L100</m:msub>=1.294,<m:msub>R100</m:msub>=1.301;</m> the exact average is between these values.</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572554311">
<p id="fs-id1170572554313"><emphasis effect="bold">[T]</emphasis> <m>y=\text{ tan } x</m> over the interval <m>[0,\frac{\pi}{4}];</m> the exact solution is <m>\frac{2 \text{ ln }(2)\pi}.</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170571612045">
<p id="fs-id1170571612047"><emphasis effect="bold">[T]</emphasis> <m>y=\frac{x+1}{\sqrt{4-x^2}}</m> over the interval <m>[-1,1];</m> the exact solution is <m>\frac{\pi}{6}.</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170571637416">
<p id="fs-id1170571637418"><m><m:msub>L100</m:msub> × (\frac{1}{2})=0.5178,<m:msub>R100</m:msub> × (\frac{1}{2})=0.5294</m></p>
</solution>

<p id="fs-id1170571637475">In the following exercises, compute the average value using the left Riemann sums <emphasis effect="italics">L<sub>N</sub></emphasis> for <m>N=1,10,100.</m> How does the accuracy compare with the given exact value?</p>

<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170571817346">
<p id="fs-id1170571817348"><emphasis effect="bold">[T]</emphasis> <m>y=x^2-4</m> over the interval <m>[0,2];</m> the exact solution is <m>-\frac{8}{3}.</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572292384">
<p id="fs-id1170572292386"><emphasis effect="bold">[T]</emphasis> <m>y=x<m:msup>e}{<m:msup>x}{2</m:msup></m:msup></m> over the interval <m>[0,2];</m> the exact solution is <m>\frac{1}{4}(e^4-1).</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170572373488">
<p id="fs-id1170572373490"><m>L_1=0,<m:msub>L10</m:msub> × (\frac{1}{2})=8.743493,<m:msub>L100</m:msub> × (\frac{1}{2})=12.861728.</m> The exact answer <m>\approx 26.799,</m> so <m>L</m><sub>100</sub> is not accurate.</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572373581">
<p id="fs-id1170572373583"><emphasis effect="bold">[T]</emphasis> <m>y=<m:msup>(\frac{1}{2})x</m:msup></m> over the interval <m>[0,4];</m> the exact solution is <m>\frac{1}{5}{64 \text{ ln }(2)}.</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572380131">
<p id="fs-id1170572380133"><emphasis effect="bold">[T]</emphasis> <m>y=x \sin(x^2)</m> over the interval <m>[-\pi,0];</m> the exact solution is <m>\frac{\text{ cos }(\pi^2)-1}{2\pi}.</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170572172957">
<p id="fs-id1170572172959"><m>L_1 × (\frac{1}{\pi})=1.352,<m:msub>L10</m:msub> × (\frac{1}{\pi})=-0.1837,<m:msub>L100</m:msub> × (\frac{1}{\pi})=-0.2956.</m> The exact answer <m>\approx -0.303,</m> so <m>L</m><sub>100</sub> is not accurate to first decimal.</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170571557785">
<p id="fs-id1170571557787">Suppose that <m>A=\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫02\pi</m:msubsup><m:msup>\sin2</m:msup>tdt} </m> and <m>B=\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫02\pi</m:msubsup><m:msup>\text{ cos }2</m:msup>tdt} .</m> Show that <m>A+B=2\pi</m> and <m>A=B\text{ . }</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572572944">
<p id="fs-id1170572572946">Suppose that <m>A=\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫-\pi\text{ / }4}{\pi\text{ / }4</m:msubsup><m:msup>\text{ sec }2</m:msup>tdt} =\pi</m> and <m>B=\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫-\pi\text{ / }4}{\pi\text{ / }4</m:msubsup><m:msup>\text{ tan }2</m:msup>tdt} .</m> Show that <m>A-B=\frac{\pi}{2}.</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170571614588">
<p id="fs-id1170571614590">Use <m><m:msup>\text{ tan }2</m:msup>\theta +1=<m:msup>\text{ sec }2</m:msup>\theta .</m> Then, <m>B-A=\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫-\pi\text{ / }4}{\pi\text{ / }4</m:msubsup>1dx} =\frac{\pi}{2}.</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572610142">
<p id="fs-id1170572610144">Show that the average value of <m><m:msup>\sin2</m:msup>t</m> over <m>[0,2\pi]</m> is equal to 1/2 Without further calculation, determine whether the average value of <m><m:msup>\sin2</m:msup>t</m> over <m>[0,\pi]</m> is also equal to 1/2.</p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572371992">
<p id="fs-id1170572371994">Show that the average value of <m><m:msup>\text{ cos }2</m:msup>t</m> over <m>[0,2\pi]</m> is equal to <m>1\text{ / }2.</m> Without further calculation, determine whether the average value of <m><m:msup>\text{ cos }2</m:msup>(t)</m> over <m>[0,\pi]</m> is also equal to <m>1\text{ / }2.</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170572372083">
<p id="fs-id1170572372085"><m>\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫02\pi</m:msubsup><m:msup>\text{ cos }2</m:msup>tdt} =\pi,</m> so divide by the length 2<m>\pi</m> of the interval. <m><m:msup>\text{ cos }2</m:msup>t</m> has period <m>\pi</m>, so yes, it is true.</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572560196">
<p id="fs-id1170572560198">Explain why the graphs of a quadratic function (parabola) <m>p(x)</m> and a linear function <m>ℓ(x)</m> can intersect in at most two points. Suppose that <m>p(a)=ℓ(a)</m> and <m>p(b)=ℓ(b),</m> and that <m>\displaystyle{\int_{a}^{b} p(t)dt} \gt \displaystyle{\int_{a}^{b} ℓ(t)dt} .</m> Explain why <m>\displaystyle{\int_{c}^{d} p(t)} \gt \displaystyle{\int_{c}^{d} ℓ(t)dt} </m> whenever <m>a\leq c\lt d\leq b.</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572332688">
<p id="fs-id1170572332690">Suppose that parabola <m>p(x)=ax^2+bx+c</m> opens downward <m>(a\lt 0)</m> and has a vertex of <m>y=\frac{-b}{2a}\gt 0.</m> For which interval <m>[A,B]</m> is <m>\displaystyle{\int_{A}^{B} (ax^2+bx+c)dx} </m> as large as possible?</p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170572274652">
<p id="fs-id1170572274654">The integral is maximized when one uses the largest interval on which <m>p</m> is nonnegative. Thus, <m>A=\frac{-b-\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</m> and <m>B=\frac{-b+\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}.</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572274743">
<p id="fs-id1170572274745">Suppose <m>[a,b]</m> can be subdivided into subintervals <m>a=a_0\lt a_1\lt a_2\lt  \cdots \lt a_N=b</m> such that either <m>f\geq 0</m> over <m>[<m:msub>ai-1</m:msub>,a_i]</m> or <m>f\leq 0</m> over <m>[<m:msub>ai-1</m:msub>,a_i].</m> Set <m>A_i=\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫<m:msub>ai-1</m:msub>}{a_i</m:msubsup>f(t)dt} .</m></p>
<ol marker="(a)">
<li>Explain why <m>\displaystyle{\int_{a}^{b} f(t)dt} =A_1+A_2+ \cdots +A_N.</m></li>
<li>Then, explain why <m>|\displaystyle{\int_{a}^{b} f(t)dt} |\leq \displaystyle{\int_{a}^{b} |f(t)|dt} .</m></li>
</ol>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572330166">
<p id="fs-id1170572330169">Suppose <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are continuous functions such that <m>\displaystyle{\int_{c}^{d} f(t)dt} \leq \displaystyle{\int_{c}^{d} g(t)dt} </m> for every subinterval <m>[c,d]</m> of <m>[a,b].</m> Explain why <m>f(x)\leq g(x)</m> for all values of <m>x</m>.</p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170571596324">
<p id="fs-id1170571596326">If <m>f(t_0)\gt g(t_0)</m> for some <m>t_0∈[a,b],</m> then since <m>f-g</m> is continuous, there is an interval containing <m>t</m><sub>0</sub> such that <m>f(t)\gt g(t)</m> over the interval <m>[c,d],</m> and then <m>\displaystyle{\int_{d}^{d} f(t)dt} \gt \displaystyle{\int_{c}^{d} g(t)dt} </m> over this interval.</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572557929">
<p id="fs-id1170572557931">Suppose the average value of <m>f</m> over <m>[a,b]</m> is 1 and the average value of <m>f</m> over <m>[b,c]</m> is 1 where <m>a\lt c\lt b.</m> Show that the average value of <m>f</m> over <m>[a,c]</m> is also 1.</p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572370995">
<p id="fs-id1170572370997">Suppose that <m>[a,b]</m> can be partitioned. taking <m>a=a_0\lt a_1\lt  \cdots \lt a_N=b</m> such that the average value of <m>f</m> over each subinterval <m>[<m:msub>ai-1</m:msub>,a_i]=1</m> is equal to 1 for each <m>i=1\text{ ,…, } N.</m> Explain why the average value of <m>f</m> over <m>[a,b]</m> is also equal to 1.</p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170572370325">
<p id="fs-id1170572370327">The integral of <m>f</m> over an interval is the same as the integral of the average of <m>f</m> over that interval. Thus, <md><mrow>\displaystyle{\int_{a}^{b} f(t)dt} =\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫a_0}{a_1</m:msubsup>f(t)dt} +\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫a_1}{a_2</m:msubsup>f(t)dt} + \cdots +\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫<m:msub>aN+1</m:msub>}{a_N</m:msubsup>f(t)dt} =\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫a_0}{a_1</m:msubsup>1dt} +\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫a_1}{a_2</m:msubsup>1dt} + \cdots +\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫<m:msub>aN+1</m:msub>}{a_N</m:msubsup>1dt} </mrow><mrow>\amp =(a_1-a_0)+(a_2-a_1)+ \cdots +(a_N-<m:msub>aN-1</m:msub>)=a_N-a_0=b-a.</mrow></m> Dividing through by <m>b-a</m> gives the desired identity.</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572353400">
<p id="fs-id1170572353403">Suppose that for each <m>i</m> such that <m>1\leq i\leq N</m> one has <m>\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫i-1i</m:msubsup>f(t)dt} =i.</m> Show that <m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{N} f(t)dt} =\frac{N(N+1)2}.</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572390663">
<p id="fs-id1170572390665">Suppose that for each <m>i</m> such that <m>1\leq i\leq N</m> one has <m>\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫i-1i</m:msubsup>f(t)dt} =i^2.</m> Show that <m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{N} f(t)dt} =\frac{N(N+1)}{(2N+1)6}.</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170571654042">
<p id="fs-id1170571654044"><m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{N} f(t)dt} =\displaystyle{\sum_{i=1}^n  \displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫i-1i</m:msubsup>f(t)dt} } =\displaystyle{\sum_{i=1}^n  i^2} =\frac{N(N+1)}{(2N+1)6}</m></p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572447512">
<p id="fs-id1170572447514"><emphasis effect="bold">[T]</emphasis> Compute the left and right Riemann sums <m>L</m><sub>10</sub> and <m>R</m><sub>10</sub> and their average <m>\frac{<m:msub>L10</m:msub>+<m:msub>R10</m:msub>2}</m> for <m>f(t)=t^2</m> over <m>[0,1].</m> Given that <m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{1} t^2dt} =0.<m:mover accent="true">33–</m:mover>,</m> to how many decimal places is <m>\frac{<m:msub>L10</m:msub>+<m:msub>R10</m:msub>2}</m> accurate?</p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572370443">
<p id="fs-id1170572370445"><emphasis effect="bold">[T]</emphasis> Compute the left and right Riemann sums, <m>L</m><sub>10</sub> and <m>R</m><sub>10</sub>, and their average <m>\frac{<m:msub>L10</m:msub>+<m:msub>R10</m:msub>2}</m> for <m>f(t)=(4-t^2)</m> over <m>[1,2].</m> Given that <m>\displaystyle{\int_{1}^{2} (4-t^2)dt} =1.<m:mover accent="true">66–</m:mover>,</m> to how many decimal places is <m>\frac{<m:msub>L10</m:msub>+<m:msub>R10</m:msub>2}</m> accurate?</p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170571543367">
<p id="fs-id1170571543369"><m><m:msub>L10</m:msub>=1.815,<m:msub>R10</m:msub>=1.515,\frac{<m:msub>L10</m:msub>+<m:msub>R10</m:msub>2}=1.665,</m> so the estimate is accurate to two decimal places.</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170571543430">
<p id="fs-id1170571543432">If <m>\displaystyle{\int_{1}^{5} \sqrt{1+t^4}dt} =41.7133...,</m> what is <m>\displaystyle{\int_{1}^{5} \sqrt{1+u^4}du} ?</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572367461">
<p id="fs-id1170572367464">Estimate <m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{1} tdt} </m> using the left and right endpoint sums, each with a single rectangle. How does the average of these left and right endpoint sums compare with the actual value <m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{1} tdt} ?</m></p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170572367515">
<p id="fs-id1170572367517">The average is <m>1\text{ / }2,</m> which is equal to the integral in this case.</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170571838064">
<p id="fs-id1170571838066">Estimate <m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{1} tdt} </m> by comparison with the area of a single rectangle with height equal to the value of <m>t</m> at the midpoint <m>t=\frac{1}{2}.</m> How does this midpoint estimate compare with the actual value <m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{1} tdt} ?</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170571838158">
<p id="fs-id1170571838161">From the graph of <m>\sin(2\pix)</m> shown:</p>
<ol marker="(a)">
<li>Explain why <m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{1} \sin(2\pit)dt} =0.</m></li>
<li>Explain why, in general, <m>\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫aa+1</m:msubsup>\sin(2\pit)dt} =0</m> for any value of <m>a</m>.
<description>"A graph of the function f(x) = sin(2pi*x) over [0, 2]. The function is shaded over [.7, 1] above the curve and below to x axis, over [1,1.5] under the curve and above the x axis, and over [1.5, 1.7] above the curve and under the x axis. The graph is antisymmetric with respect o t = ½ over [0,1].">
<image source="CNX_Calc_Figure_05_02_207.jpg" width="50%">

</li>
</ol>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170571779592">
<p id="fs-id1170571779594">a. The graph is antisymmetric with respect to <m>t=\frac{1}{2}</m> over <m>[0,1],</m> so the average value is zero. b. For any value of <m>a</m>, the graph between <m>[a,a+1]</m> is a shift of the graph over <m>[0,1],</m> so the net areas above and below the axis do not change and the average remains zero.</p>
</solution>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572643336">
<p id="fs-id1170572643338">If <m>f</m> is 1-periodic <m>(f(t+1)=f(t)),</m> odd, and integrable over <m>[0,1],</m> is it always true that <m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{1} f(t)dt} =0?</m></p>
</statement>


<!-- Move title outside statement--> <statement id="fs-id1170572350691">
<p id="fs-id1170572350693">If <m>f</m> is 1-periodic and <m>\displaystyle{\int_{0}^{1} f(t)dt} =A,</m> is it necessarily true that <m>\displaystyle{<m:msubsup>∫a1+a</m:msubsup>f(t)dt} =A</m> for all <m>A</m>?</p>
</statement>
<solution id="fs-id1170572398846">
<p id="fs-id1170572398848">Yes, the integral over any interval of length 1 is the same.</p>
</solution>

</section>
</content>
<glossary>
<definition id="fs-id1170572398858">
<term>average value of a function</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1170572398864">(or <emphasis effect="bold">f_{\text{ave}} </emphasis>) the average value of a function on an interval can be found by calculating the definite integral of the function and dividing that value by the length of the interval</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1170572398877">
<term>definite integral</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1170572398882">a primary operation of calculus; the area between the curve and the <m>x</m>-axis over a given interval is a definite integral</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1170572398892">
<term>integrable function</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1170572398898">a function is integrable if the limit defining the integral exists; in other words, if the limit of the Riemann sums as <m>n</m> goes to infinity exists</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1170572398909">
<term>integrand</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1170572398914">the function to the right of the integration symbol; the integrand includes the function being integrated</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1170572398919">
<term>limits of integration</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1170572398925">these values appear near the top and bottom of the integral sign and define the interval over which the function should be integrated</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1170572398930">
<term>net signed area</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1170572398936">the area between a function and the <m>x</m>-axis such that the area below the <m>x</m>-axis is subtracted from the area above the <m>x</m>-axis; the result is the same as the definite integral of the function</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1170572398956">
<term>total area</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1170572398962">total area between a function and the <m>x</m>-axis is calculated by adding the area above the <m>x</m>-axis and the area below the <m>x</m>-axis; the result is the same as the definite integral of the absolute value of the function</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1170571613095">
<term>variable of integration</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1170571613101">indicates which variable you are integrating with respect to; if it is <m>x</m>, then the function in the integrand is followed by <emphasis effect="italics">dx</emphasis></meaning>
</definition>
</glossary>
</document>
?>
